title: Statistical Hypothesis Testing Using the Delta Method
text: online /B testing, often face significant practical challenge: randomization unit differs analysis unit. Typically, control treatment groups randomly assigned user level, metrics—click-rate—measured granular level (e.g., per page-view). case, randomization unit user, analysis unit page-view. discrepancy raises concerns statistical hypothesis testing, assumes data points independent identically distributed (..d.). Specifically, single user can generate multiple page-views, user may different probability clicking. Consequently, data may exhibit within-user correlation, thereby violating ..d. assumption. standard Z-test applied correlated data, resulting p-values follow expected uniform distribution null hypothesis. result, smaller p-values tend occur frequently even true difference, increasing risk falsely detecting significant difference.  address problem, Deng et al. (2018) proposed modified statistical hypothesis testing method. approach replaces standard variance estimation formula Z-test approximate formula derived via Delta method, accounts within-user correlation. simplify application method, deltatest package developed. illustrate use package, prepare data frame includes columns number clicks page-views aggregated user. data frame also contains column indicating whether user assigned control treatment group. statistical hypothesis test using Delta method can performed data follows: version Z-test yields p-values follow expected uniform distribution null hypothesis, even within-user correlation present.
code: library(dplyr)  n_user <- 2000  set.seed(314) data <- deltatest::generate_dummy_data(n_user) |>    mutate(group = if_else(group == 0, "control", "treatment")) |>   group_by(user_id, group) |>    summarise(clicks = sum(metric), pageviews = n(), .groups = "drop")  data #> # A tibble: 2,000 × 4 #>    user_id group     clicks pageviews #>      <int> <chr>      <int>     <int> #>  1       1 treatment      1         6 #>  2       2 treatment      2        11 #>  3       3 control        0        17 #>  4       4 control        4        12 #>  5       5 control        5        10 #>  6       6 control        1        15 #>  7       7 control        2         6 #>  8       8 treatment      2        11 #>  9       9 treatment      2        16 #> 10      10 control        0        17 #> # ℹ 1,990 more rows library(deltatest)  deltatest(data, clicks / pageviews, by = group) #>  #>  Two Sample Z-test Using the Delta Method #>  #> data:  clicks/pageviews by group #> Z = 0.31437, p-value = 0.7532 #> alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between control and treatment is not equal to 0 #> 95 percent confidence interval: #>  -0.01410593  0.01949536 #> sample estimates: #>   mean in control mean in treatment        difference  #>       0.245959325       0.248654038       0.002694713

title: Statistical Hypothesis Testing Using the Delta Method
text: run deltatest, need prepare appropriately aggregated data frame. data frame must include columns numerator denominator metric, aggregated randomization unit (typically, user). example: metric click-rate per page-view, numerator number clicks, denominator number page-views. metric conversion rate per session, numerator number conversions (converted sessions), denominator number sessions. Note denominator match analysis unit. deltatest package provides generate_dummy_data function create dummy data. generates metric values per page-view, need aggregate data user. data frame includes user_id column, column required run deltatest.
code: library(dplyr)  n_user <- 2000  set.seed(314) data <- deltatest::generate_dummy_data(n_user) |>   group_by(user_id, group) |>   summarise(clicks = sum(metric), pageviews = n(), .groups = "drop")  data #> # A tibble: 2,000 × 4 #>    user_id group clicks pageviews #>      <int> <int>  <int>     <int> #>  1       1     1      1         6 #>  2       2     1      2        11 #>  3       3     0      0        17 #>  4       4     0      4        12 #>  5       5     0      5        10 #>  6       6     0      1        15 #>  7       7     0      2         6 #>  8       8     1      2        11 #>  9       9     1      2        16 #> 10      10     0      0        17 #> # ℹ 1,990 more rows

text: default, deltatest tests difference two groups. specify type = 'relative_change', tests rate change, .e., \((\mu_{t} - \mu_{c}) / \mu_{c}\) \(\mu_c\) \(\mu_t\) represent mean values control group treatment group, respectively.

title: Two Sample Z-Test for Ratio Metrics Using the Delta Method — deltatest
text: Performs two sample Z-test compare ratio metrics two groups using delta method. Delta method used estimate variance accounting correlation numerator denominator ratio metrics.

title: Two Sample Z-Test for Ratio Metrics Using the Delta Method — deltatest
code: deltatest(   data,   formula,   by,   group_names = "auto",   type = c("difference", "relative_change"),   bias_correction = FALSE,   alternative = c("two.sided", "less", "greater"),   conf.level = 0.95,   na.rm = FALSE,   quiet = FALSE )

title: Two Sample Z-Test for Ratio Metrics Using the Delta Method — deltatest
text: data data.frame containing numerator denominator columns ratio metric, aggregated randomization unit. also includes column indicating assigned group (control treatment). example, randomizing user metric click-rate (CTR) per page-view, numerator number clicks per user, denominator number page views per user. formula expression representing ratio metric. can written three styles: standard formula x/y ~ group, lambda formula ~ x/y, NSE expression x/y. character string symbol indicates group column. group column specified formula argument, required. group_names character vector length 2 "auto". specifies two strings contained group column control group treatment group. first string considered control group, second string considered treatment group. "auto" specified, interpreted specifying strings group column sorted lexicographical order. default "auto". type character string specifying test type. "difference" (default), hypothesis test evaluates difference means ratio metric two groups. "relative_change", evaluates relative change \((\mu_2 - \mu_1) / \mu_1\) instead. can specify just initial letter. bias_correction logical value indicating whether correction mean metric performed using second-order term Taylor expansion. default FALSE. alternative character string specifying alternative hypothesis, must one "two.sided" (default), "greater", "less". can specify just initial letter. conf.level numeric value specifying confidence level interval. default 0.95. na.rm logical value. TRUE, rows containing NA values data excluded analysis. default FALSE. quiet logical value indicating whether messages displayed execution function. default FALSE.
